{"cursor":"5286","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox royalty\n| type = monarch name = Fruela II image = Fruela2.jpg imgw = 200px caption =\n| succession = King of Asturias reign = 910–925 coronation = predecessor =\n| Alfonso III successor = Alfonso IV succession1 = King of LeÃ³n reign1 =\n| 924–925 coronation1 = predecessor1 = OrdoÃ±o II successor1 = Alfonso IV\n| succession2 = King of Galicia reign2 = 924–925 coronation2 =\n| predecessor2 = OrdoÃ±o II successor2 = Alfonso FrÃ³ilaz spouse = Nunilo Urraca bint Abd Allah issue = Alfonso FrÃ³ilaz Ramiro Froilaz OrdoÃ±o Froilaz issue-link = issue-pipe = full name = house = Beni Alfons house-\n| type = Dynasty father = Alfonso III of Asturias mother = Jimena of Pamplona\n| birth_date = c. 875 birth_place = death_date = July 925 death_place =\n| burial_place = religion = Roman Catholicism }}\n'Fruela II' ('Froila II') (c. 875âJuly 925) was the King of Asturias from the\ndeath of his father, Alfonso III of Asturias, in 910 to his own death. When his\nfather died, the kingdom was divided, with the third son, Fruela, taking the\noriginal portion (Asturias); the second, OrdoÃ±o, taking Galicia; and the eldest,\nGarcÃ­a, taking LeÃ³n. As king of Asturias, he had the job of consolidating the\nregion later called Castile and keeping its counts in check.\n\nFruela's mother was Jimena of Pamplona. He himself married twice, first to a\nwoman of unknown origin named Nunila or Nunilona (late sources make her a member\nof the Basque Jimenez dynasty, but this is unsupported). His second wife,\nUrraca, according to Ibn Khaldun and Ibn Hazm, was the daughter of the Banu Qasi\ngovernor of Tudela. They were married by 917.\n\nFruela maintained good relations with his brother OrdoÃ±o, who had the hegemony.\nThey cooperated in the Reconquista and Fruela undersigned OrdoÃ±o's diplomas as\nFroila rex with his second wife, Urraca regina. When OrdoÃ±o died in 924, the\nmagnates ignored his heirs and elected Fruela king. Fruela had never been\npopular with the nobles and his subjects and his election has been doubted by\nsome, who see it as a likely usurpation. He assassinated Gebuldo and Aresindo,\nsons of Olmundo, who claimed descent from King Witiza, and thus further\nalienated the nobility. For this, one chronicler relates, he was condemned to a\nreign of only fourteen months. According to RamÃ³n MenÃ©ndez Pidal, he exiled the\nbishop Frunimio of LeÃ³n, a relation of Olmundo. Whatever the case, he did reign\nfor a mere fourteen more months and died in early summer 925, some say after\nhaving contracted leprosy. Following Fruela's death, there were several\ncompeting claimants to his lands, including his younger brother Ramiro (who\nappears to have married the widowed queen Urraca bint Qasi and used the royal\ntitle but was eventually unsuccessful), and the sons of his brother OrdoÃ±o II,\nalong with his own young sons. There is some debate as to the immediate\nsuccession, although eventually his family lost out to that of brother OrdoÃ±o.\n\nAccording to the Bishop Pelayo, he left three sons by Nunila: Alfonso, OrdoÃ±o,\nand Ramiro. Ibn Khaldun gives OrdoÃ±o and Ramiro to Urraca and leaves open the\npossibility of other children by either wife.\n","linknr":182,"url":"Fruela_II_of_León","recorded":1375075537,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Fruela_II_of_Asturias&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Fruela_II_of_Asturias&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Fruela_II_of_Asturias","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipe